gov/text-services/word-coordinates-service"}], "segment_id": "/service/ndnp/arhi/batch_arhi_interstellar_ver01/data/sn90050272/00513688714/1920081301/0259.xml", "segments": [{"access_restricted": false, "aka": ["http://www.loc.gov/resource/sn90050272/1920-08-13/ed-1/?sp=7"], "batch": ["arhi_interstellar_ver01"], "campaigns": [], "composite_location": ["0/united states/", "1/united states/arkansas/", "2/united states/arkansas/independence/", "3/united states/arkansas/independence/batesville/"], "contributor": ["arkansas state archives"], "date": "1920-08-13", "dates": ["1920-08-13"], "description": ["BUSINESS CRISIS OVER U S IN SPRING Men of Affairs Knew It But Kept Silent That a serious danger of business crisis did exist in the early spring is now admitted by men who were fa miliar with conditions They knew it at the time but thought that prudence required silence Now in these first days of the new fiscal year perhaps the most gratifying report to be made is one which tells of the passing of the crisis ami the slow but steady re lief from the embarrassments which business met with in the winter and early spring There was no real danger of money panic but business men reported in the spring that they were unable t forecast the future for more than a few weeks They did not know whether they would be able to secure needed accommodations from the banks They feared lest their loans would be called The farmers felt the pressure and were obliged to can cel orders for tractors and other farm implements Many of the sales agents were compelled to return to the manufacturers the tractors which had been placed with them for sale We now know that in the late fall"], "digitized": true, "extract_timestamp": "2024-12-03T00:42:28.863Z", "group": ["ndnp/arhi", "arkansas-state-archives-awardee"], "hassegments": false, "id": "http://www.loc.gov/resource/sn90050272/1920-08-13/ed-1/?sp=7", "image_url": ["https://tile.loc.gov/image-services/iiif/service:ndnp:arhi:batch_arhi_interstellar_